  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Fleeting Life
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    How can I trust in this fleeting life?
    Old age and sickness vie to wear me down.
    The sun and moon are rings beneath my ears,
    The cosmos, an arrow through my heart.

    Wind enters my sleeves on the clear day—
    I lean upon my staff;
    Dew soaks my robes in the night—
    I coax the lute to sing.

    A thousand worries settle into silence,
    And heaven and earth stretch fathomless before me.
  footnotes:
    - The 'rings beneath my ears' and 'arrow through my heart' are metaphors for the relentless passage of time and the inexorable advance of age and mortality.
    - The imagery of wind, dew, staff, and lute suggests the poet's acceptance of natural processes and his turn toward music and contemplation as sources of solace.
    - The closing couplet reflects a Buddhist or Daoist sensibility—that in surrendering to the vastness of the cosmos, the mind finds peace.
